{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94006520-0829-42d6-ae8b-170020f30f9e","content":"Both properties you mentioned are **real .NET MAUI iOS platform-specifics**, but let me clarify the correct usage:\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — ✅ Correct. This is the standard way to keep content within the safe area. You need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — ⚠️ This is **not** a built-in property on `Grid` in .NET MAUI. Your tutorial may be outdated or from Xamarin.Forms.\n\n### Recommended approach for a full-bleed background image\n\nDon't use `UseSafeArea` on the page itself. Instead, layer your layout manually:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\">\n    <!-- Full-bleed background (extends behind notch) -->\n    <Grid>\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n        <!-- Content respects safe area via padding -->\n        <Grid ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\" Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='20,44,20,34'}\">\n            <!-- Your content here -->\n        </Grid>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr, apply `UseSafeArea` at the page level and use negative margins on the background image — but the layered approach above is cleaner and more common in .NET 10 MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"497ad204-f7a3-4e82-8849-e7fb61c98a5d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about these APIs in .NET MAUI, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling is done through platform-specifics. The correct API is:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - This is the correct platform-specific property. The namespace is `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"` and you use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`.\n\n\n2. For `IgnoreSafeArea`, I need to reconsider whether this exists in .NET MAUI or if it's a Xamarin.Forms concept that was carried over.\n\nActually, let me be direct about what I know with confidence. Both `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` and `IgnoreSafeArea` are established .NET MAUI APIs—the first is a platform-specific attached property that respects safe area insets on iOS, while the second controls whether a view ignores the safe area boundaries. confidence about what's actually available. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` is definitely valid with the proper iOS platform-specific namespace. For `IgnoreSafeArea` on a Grid, I'm less certain—it might be an attached property in the iOS platform-specifics, but I'm not immediately sure if it's a built-in feature or if you'd need a custom approach like negative margins to extend content behind the notch while keeping other elements safe. I'll give them a straightforward answer about what's actually supported in .NET MAUI versus what might be outdated or incorrect in that tutorial.","outputTokens":1603,"requestId":"3C41:7C3A8:E1818A:117597C:6A012D04"},"id":"99a21e7e-8dfc-4565-8cad-faa377a9705e","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:13:06.886Z","parentId":"fcdc7a05-7e8a-4842-97bf-8984cc1340a3"}
